    {
      "id": "compare_call_debit_spread",
      "message": "Compare a long call and a call debit spread for earnings",
      "notes": "Compare tradeoffs, do not crown a winner.",
      "passed": true,
      "provider": "fallback",
      "model": "deterministic-options-coach",
      "used_fallback": true,
      "mode": "strategy_explainer",
      "answer": "For an earnings trade, a long call is the cleaner upside bet: one contract, max loss is the premium, and upside is open-ended. The problem is that it pays full price for time and implied volatility, so IV crush can hurt even if direction is right.\n\nA call debit spread buys one call and sells a higher-strike call. Max loss is still the net debit paid, but max gain is capped. The trade-off is lower cost and lower breakeven pressure versus giving up the huge upside tail.",
